        {
          "id": 67568,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">The local anesthetic is required in the unionized form for penetrating the neuronal membrane.</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 67569,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">The local anesthetic approaches its receptor from the intraneuronal face of the Na+ channel.</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 67570,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">The local anesthetic binds to its receptor mainly when the Na+ channel is in the resting state.</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 67571,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">The local anesthetic combines with its receptor in the ionized cationic form.</span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Which of the following statements is not true of local anesthetics?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q3259979",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 36261,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        4
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. C) The local anaesthetic binds to its receptor mainly when the Na+ channel is in the resting state</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Local anesthetics </strong>primarily bind to <strong>their receptor,</strong> the <strong>voltage-gated sodium channel,</strong> when it is in the <strong>activated (open) or inactivated</strong> state,<strong> not</strong> when it is in the<strong> resting state.</strong> This interaction <strong>blocks sodium influx</strong>, inhibiting the<strong> propagation of action potentials </strong>and achieving<strong> local anesthesia</strong>. The <strong>ionized form </strong>of the <strong>local anesthetic </strong>is essential for <strong>binding within the channel</strong>, but the<strong> unionized form </strong>is necessary for<strong> penetration </strong>through the <strong>neuronal lipid membrane </strong>to reach the <strong>intracellular site of action</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A. The local anesthetic is required in the unionized form for penetrating the neuronal membrane:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> <strong>True</strong>, as the <strong>unionized form </strong>is more <strong>lipophilic </strong>and can cross<strong> lipid membranes </strong>more easily.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B. The local anesthetic approaches its receptor from the intraneuronal face of the Na+ channel:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> <strong>True</strong>, once inside the <strong>neuron, </strong>the local anesthetic can access and<strong> bind to the inner portion of the sodium channel.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D. The local anesthetic combines with its receptor in the ionized cationic form:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong> True,</strong> the <strong>ionized form </strong>of the drug is the <strong>active form </strong>that interacts with the <strong>sodium channel to block nerve conduction.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective</span></u></strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">:</span></u></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Understanding the <strong>dual nature of local anesthetics&#39; </strong>interaction with <strong>sodium channels is crucial</strong>. They must be capable of <strong>both lipophilic and hydrophilic behavior </strong>to effectively penetrate <strong>nerve cells and exert their blocking action</strong>, highlighting the importance of their<strong> molecular structure in clinical efficacy</strong>.</span></span></span></p>",
