        {
          "id": 67511,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Adrenaline increases the duration of action of lignocaine when used for infiltration anaesthesia</span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">All the following statements about lignocaine are true except:</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q4526414",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 36262,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        4
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. C) It is given orally for treatment of cardiac arrhythmias</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Lignocaine (lidocaine) </strong>is primarily used as a<strong> local anesthetic and antiarrhythmic agent</strong>. However, due to its <strong>high first-pass metabolism in the liver</strong>, it is <strong>not effective </strong>when given <strong>orally </strong>for the treatment of <strong>cardiac arrhythmias</strong>. It must be<strong> administered intravenously</strong> to<strong> bypass hepatic metabolism </strong>and be effective in<strong> controlling cardiac arrhythmias</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong><u> </u></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A. It blocks active sodium channels with more affinity than resting sodium channels:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> <strong>True</strong>,<strong> lignocaine </strong>preferentially binds to and<strong> blocks sodium channels </strong>in their <strong>active or open </strong>state, which contributes to its <strong>effectiveness as a local anesthetic.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B. It can cause cardiotoxicity:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> <strong>True, </strong>at <strong>high blood concentrations,</strong> lignocaine can have <strong>toxic effects on the heart, </strong>including <strong>arrhythmias and cardiac arrest.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D. Adrenaline increases the duration of action of lignocaine when used for infiltration anesthesia:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> <strong>True</strong>, <strong>adrenaline (epinephrine) </strong>is added to <strong>lignocaine </strong>in infiltration anesthesia to cause<strong> vasoconstriction, </strong>which <strong>reduces blood flow </strong>and slows the <strong>absorption of lignocaine, </strong>thereby <strong>prolonging its duration of action and reducing systemic toxicity.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Understand that<strong> lignocaine is ineffective orally for cardiac arrhythmias </strong>due to its <strong>high first-pass metabolism</strong>, necessitating <strong>intravenous administration for therapeutic effectiveness.</strong></span></span></span></p>",
